{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-97dd5499020fa490", "type": "tool_result", "content": "600\tC\n601\t\n602\t0.30\n603\t\n604\tbest WER\n605\t\n606\tworst WER\n607\t\n608\t0.25\n609\t\n610\tBad-reference acceptance rate\n611\t\n612\tA\n613\tD\n614\t\n615\tB\n616\t\n617\t0.20\n618\t\n619\tE\n620\t\n621\tF\n622\t\n623\t0.15\n624\t\n625\t0.10\n626\t\n627\tH\n628\t0.05\n629\t\n630\tJ\n631\tG\n632\t\n633\tK\n634\t\n635\tI\n636\t\n637\t0.00\n638\t5.0\n639\t\n640\t5.5\n641\t\n642\t6.0\n643\t\n644\t6.5\n645\t\n646\t7.0\n647\t\n648\t7.5\n649\t\n650\t8.0\n651\t\n652\t8.5\n653\t\n654\t9.0\n655\t\n656\tVoxPopuli WER (lower is better) — Open ASR Leaderboard, %\n657\t\n658\tFigure 4. Cross-model audit on VoxPopuli-English. WER (%) from the June 2026 Open ASR Leaderboard [30]. Bad-reference\n659\tacceptance: the rate at which each model returned reference transcripts verbatim on cases where the reference was identified as\n660\trequiring a correction\n661\t\n662\tThese preliminary results establish benchmark optimization as a measurable phenomenon across modern ASR systems\n663\tand motivate the more detailed analyses that follow. In future work, we will extend this study and offer deeper analysis to\n664\tbetter characterize the prevalence and mechanisms of benchmark optimization. More broadly, these findings reinforce the\n665\tneed for real world, withheld evaluation sets that remain inaccessible during model development, reducing opportunities\n666\tfor benchmark-specific optimization and providing a more faithful estimate of real world transcription performance.\n667\tThis motivation aligns with recent community efforts toward private-data evaluation, such as the Hugging Face Open\n668\tASR Leaderboard’s 4 introduction of hidden test sets. Our results suggest that such withheld evaluations are not merely\n669\tdesirable but necessary, as standard public benchmarks alone may substantially overestimate real world generalization.\n670\t\n671\t4 huggingface.co/blog/open-asr-leaderboard-private-data\n672\t\n673\t9\n674\t\n675\t\f4 Text-to-Speech Evaluation\n676\tText-to-speech (TTS) systems are increasingly expected to do more than synthesize intelligible, natural-sounding speech.\n677\tContemporary systems must preserve speaker identity, follow expressive and voice-design instructions, accurately render\n678\ttask-critical content, handle within-utterance language switching, remain stable during extended generation, and produce\n679\tspeech appropriate to the intended role and communicative setting. These capabilities can fail independently: a system\n680\tmay sound natural while drifting in speaker identity, produce expressive speech while misreading structured content, or\n681\tperform well on short utterances while degrading over longer passages. RW-Voice-EQ Bench therefore evaluates TTS\n682\tas a multidimensional capability rather than reducing performance to a single naturalness or preference score. This\n683\tsection reviews prior TTS evaluation approaches, describes the RW-Voice-EQ Bench TTS evaluation domain, presents\n684\tdimension-level results, and discusses their implications for both TTS systems and automated evaluators.\n685\t\n686\t4.1 Experimental Setup\n687\tWe evaluated 31 TTS system configurations spanning commercial APIs, proprietary research systems, and open-source\n688\tmodels. For each system, we used the provider’s default voice, voice configuration, and generation settings. The\n689\tevaluated systems were as follows; version details are provided in Section A and Table 4:\n690\t• OpenAI: TTS-1, TTS-1-HD, and GPT-4o Mini TTS.\n691\t• Google Gemini: Gemini 2.5 Flash Preview TTS, Gemini 2.5 Pro Preview TTS, and Gemini 3.1 Flash TTS\n692\tPreview.\n693\t• ElevenLabs: Eleven Multilingual v2 and Eleven v3, each evaluated through both standard TTS and voice-design\n694\tinterfaces.\n695\t• Cartesia: Sonic 3.5.\n696\t• Deepgram: Aura 2.\n697\t• Inworld: Inworld TTS 1, Inworld TTS 1 Max, Inworld TTS 2, and Inworld Voice Design.\n698\t• Kokoro: Hexgrad Kokoro-82M, evaluated through local, Modal, and Replicate deployments.\n699\t• XTTS-v2: evaluated through Modal and Replicate deployments.\n700\t• Additional open-source and hosted models: Microsoft VibeVoice-1.5B, Qwen3-TTS, Higgs Audio v2, Higgs\n701\tAudio v3, Chatterbox, Dia, IndexTTS2, Parler-TTS, Fish Speech, and CSM-1B.\n702\tEvaluation Tasks. The TTS benchmark comprised 30 evaluations organized into seven evaluation dimensions: Acting /\n703\tRole-Fit, Expressiveness, Voice Identity, Multilingual Code-Switching, Reliability, Long-Form Speaker Stability, and\n704\tAcoustic Quality. Each category used a fixed item set and a predefined scoring protocol. Individual categories contained\n705\tup to 120 prompts, although the number of applicable prompts varied according to the task design and the capabilities\n706\tsupported by each system.\n707\tTable 1 summarizes these evaluation dimensions, task counts, rating volume, generation volume, and reported measures.\n708\tThe evaluations were designed to measure distinct constructs rather than interchangeable indicators of overall synthesis\n709\tquality. For example, expressive tasks assessed whether a model realized a requested affective or pragmatic behavior,\n710\tidentity tasks assessed whether the perceived speaker remained stable under stress, and reliability tasks assessed whether\n711\ttask-critical lexical or symbolic content was rendered correctly. Results are therefore reported separately by dimension\n712\tand are not combined into a single aggregate TTS score.\n713\t\n714\t10\n715\t\n716\t\fTable 1. Summary of the RW-Voice-EQ Bench TTS benchmark, including evaluation dimensions, constituent tasks, benchmark\n717\tscale (prompts, generations, and human ratings), and reported evaluation measures.\n718\tDimension\n719\t\n720\tEvaluation(s)\n721\t\n722\tActing / Role-Fit\n723\t\n724\tAudiobook Narration, Sports Commentary, Stand-up Comedy, Humorous\n725\tDelivery, Casual/Colloquial Reading,\n726\tVocal Bursts\n727\tInferred Emotion, Instructed Emotion,\n728\tPragmatic/Subtext Delivery, Sarcasm,\n729\tExpressive Constraints, Mid-Utterance\n730\tEmotional Transitions\n731\t\n732\t#Prompts #Generations #Human Ratings Avg Ratings/Gen Reported measures & scale\n733\t66\n734\t\n735\t5,769\n736\t\n737\t112,518\n738\t\n739\t19.50 Naturalness, prosody, role fit, character\n740\tdifferentiation (1–5)\n741\t\n742\t120\n743\t\n744\t8,571\n745\t\n746\t257,731\n747\t\n748\tEmotional Stress, Neutral Baseline,\n749\tPhysical States, Prosodic Extremes,\n750\tRegister Shifts\n751\tCode-Switching (DE/ES/FR/IT/JA),\n752\tHeteronym Pronunciation\n753\tPharmaceutical Terms, Alphanumeric Strings, Structured Data Reading/Spelling\n754\tLong-Form Web Reading, Voice\n755\tIdentity – Transitions, Voice Identity –\n756\tLong Form\n757\t\n758\t96\n759\t\n760\t7,419\n761\t\n762\t71,450\n763\t\n764\t30.07 Does the delivery realize the intended\n765\taffective style, pragmatic meaning,\n766\texpressive constraints, and emotion\n767\tfrom prosody, rhythm, intensity, and\n768\tvoice quality? (1–5)\n769\t9.63 Speaker consistency / same-speaker\n770\tconfidence (1–5)\n771\t\n772\t70\n773\t\n774\t6,150\n775\t\n776\t140,960\n777\t\n778\t64\n779\t\n780\t5,566\n781\t\n782\t68,220\n783\t\n784\t80\n785\t\n786\t5,985\n787\t\n788\t134,800\n789\t\n790\tAcoustic Quality\n791\t\n792\tArtifacts; Fidelity ratings collected\n793\twithin the expression evaluations\n794\t\n795\t–\n796\t\n797\t–\n798\t\n799\t–\n800\t\n801\tOverall\n802\t\n803\tAll TTS evaluation dimensions\n804\t\n805\t496\n806\t\n807\t39,460\n808\t\n809\t785,679\n810\t\n811\tExpressiveness\n812\t\n813\tVoice Identity\n814\t\n815\tLanguage Stability\n816\tReliability\n817\t\n818\tLong-Form\n819\tSpeaker Stability\n820\t\n821\t22.92 Native-accent perception and foreignphrase comprehension (yes/no)\n822\t12.26 Correct/clear read-back of hard content;\n823\texact-content accuracy (%)\n824\t22.52 Long-form naturalness and identity\n825\tpersistence through mid-clip shifts;\n826\taudio-quality degradation opening to\n827\tmiddle/closing (volume, noise, artifacts,\n828\tpacing) (1–5, higher = less degraded)\n829\t– Naturalness, audio quality, absence of\n830\tartifacts (1–5)\n831\t19.91 Dimension-specific measures reported by dimension\n832\t\n833\tGeneration Protocol. For each model–prompt pair, we generated three audio outputs through repeated calls to the\n834\tcorresponding system under the same task conditions. Default provider settings were used unless an evaluation required a\n835\tspecific voice, reference input, language, speaking style, or voice-design instruction. Provider-specific prompt formatting\n836\twas used only where necessary to express the same intended task through different system interfaces. Prompts and\n837\texpected behaviors were fixed before model outputs were reviewed.\n838\tHuman Evaluation Protocol. Human ratings were collected through Hume’s Study Runner API. For the primary\n839\tEnglish-language evaluations, participation was restricted to self-reported native English speakers located in the\n840\tUnited States, United Kingdom, or Canada. Language stability evaluations used language-matched eligibility criteria\n841\tcorresponding to the target language.\n842\tEach audio clip was rated by at least three independent participants. Participants completed sessions containing no more\n843\tthan 10 clips, with one clip presented at a time. Sample order was randomized within each session, and participants\n844\twere not shown model names, providers, deployment backends, or other system-identifying information. Raters were\n845\tshown only the contextual information required to apply the evaluation rubric. Depending on the task, this could include\n846\tthe source text, requested emotion or speaking style, intended role or genre, expected content, or a reference voice.\n847\tParticipants were instructed to use headphones and complete the study in an environment suitable for critical listening.\n848\tAcross all TTS studies, the annotation process yielded approximately 130,000 evaluated sample records and approximately\n849\t392,000 individual rater sessions. An evaluated sample record corresponds to one audio clip within one study after\n850\taggregating the ratings of three participants. An individual rater session corresponds to one participant evaluating one\n851\taudio clip and completing all rating questions associated with that clip. The total number of criterion-level responses is\n852\ttherefore substantially larger than 392,000 because each rater session may contain multiple rating questions.\n853\tRating Rubrics and Scoring. Rating questions and response scales were defined separately for each evaluation\n854\tdimension. Most perceptual evaluations used five-point Likert scales, whereas correctness-oriented tasks used binary,\n855\tcategorical, or task-specific accuracy measures where appropriate. Acting and role-fit evaluations assessed dimensions\n856\tsuch as naturalness, prosody, and genre appropriateness; expressiveness evaluations assessed affective or pragmatic fit,\n857\tintensity, and delivery; voice-identity evaluations assessed perceived speaker consistency under expressive, physical,\n858\tregister, and duration-based stress; and acoustic-quality evaluations assessed artifacts, distortion, dropouts, instability,\n859\tand other audible degradations. Complete model and evaluation metadata are provided in Section A.\n860\t\n861\t11\n862\t\n863\t\fCell: mean ± SD\n864\t\n865\tActing /\n866\tRole-Fit\n867\t\n868\tWithin-capability rank\n869\t\n870\tExpressiveness\n871\t\n872\tVoice\n873\tIdentity\n874\t\n875\tFish Audio S2\n876\t\n877\t3.53 ± 0.01\n878\t\n879\tCartesia Sonic 3.5\n880\t\n881\t3.53 ± 0.02\n882\t\n883\t1\n884\t\n885\tLanguage\n886\tCode-Switching Reliability\n887\t3.48 ± 0.02\n888\t\n889\tGemini 2.5 Flash\n890\t\n891\t3.64 ± 0.03\n892\t\n893\t3.44 ± 0.03\n894\t\n895\t3.66 ± 0.05\n896\t\n897\tGemini 2.5 Pro\n898\t\n899\t3.63 ± 0.04\n900\t\n901\t3.32 ± 0.04\n902\t\n903\t3.89 ± 0.04\n904\t\n905\tGemini 3.1 Flash\n906\t\n907\t3.97 ± 0.04\n908\t\n909\t3.64 ± 0.04\n910\t\n911\t3.82 ± 0.04\n912\t\n913\t3.23 ± 0.03\n914\t\n915\tGPT-4o Mini TTS\n916\tOpenAI TTS-1\n917\t\n918\t3.16 ± 0.02\n919\t\n920\t3\n921\t\n922\t5\n923\t\n924\tAcoustic\n925\tQuality\n926\t\n927\t3.50 ± 0.02\n928\t\n929\t3.34 ± 0.02\n930\t\n931\t3.53 ± 0.04\n932\t\n933\t3.37 ± 0.02\n934\t\n935\t3.34 ± 0.03\n936\t\n937\t3.46 ± 0.03\n938\t\n939\t3.33 ± 0.02\n940\t\n941\t3.33 ± 0.04\n942\t\n943\t3.59 ± 0.05\n944\t\n945\t3.50 ± 0.02\n946\t\n947\tKokoro-82M\n948\t\n949\t4\n950\t\n951\tLong-Form\n952\tStability\n953\t\n954\t3.34 ± 0.03\n955\t\n956\tElevenLabs v3\n957\t\n958\t3.54 ± 0.04\n959\t\n960\t3.44 ± 0.04\n961\t\n962\tCSM-1B\n963\t3.60 ± 0.05\n964\t\n965\tDeepgram Aura-2\n966\t3.38 ± 0.03\n967\t\n968\tHiggs Audio v3\n969\t\n970\t3.52 ± 0.04\n971\t\n972\tIndexTTS-2\n973\t3.55 ± 0.02\n974\t\n975\tInworld TTS-1 Max\n976\t\n977\t3.33 ± 0.02\n978\t\n979\tInworld TTS-2\n980\t3.30 ± 0.03\n981\t\n982\tLightning v3.1\n983\t\n984\t3.46 ± 0.04\n985\t\n986\tOpenAI TTS-1 HD\n987\tQwen3-TTS\n988\t\n989\t2\n990\t\n991\t3.15 ± 0.03\n992\t\n993\tFigure 5. Top-five TTS system configurations by capability group. Cells report the capability-level mean ± standard deviation.\n994\tShading indicates within-capability rank, with darker cells denoting higher rank. Systems are ordered by the number of top-five\n995\tappearances; the horizontal rule separates systems appearing in multiple top-five lists from those appearing in only one.\n996\t\n997\tFor Likert-scale evaluations, ratings were first aggregated across the three participants assigned to each evaluated sample\n998\trecord. Repeated generations were retained as separate outputs and were subsequently summarized at the model–prompt\n999\tand model–evaluation levels. Accuracy-based tasks were scored using predefined task-specific rules. Results are\n1000\treported separately by construct and are not combined across incompatible scales into a single global TTS score.\n1001\t\n1002\t4.2 Results\n1003\tThe TTS domain of RW-Voice-EQ Bench evaluates seven evaluation dimensions: Expressiveness, Voice Identity,\n1004\tMultilingual Code-Switching, Reliability, Long-Form Speaker Stability, Acting / Role-Fit, and Acoustic Quality.\n1005\tTogether, these evaluations assess whether a system can follow expressive instructions, preserve speaker identity, handle\n1006\twithin-utterance language switching, render task-critical content reliably, remain stable during extended generation,\n1007\tmaintain acoustic quality, and produce speech appropriate to a specified role or genre.\n1008\tFigure 5 presents the five highest-scoring system configurations within each evaluation dimension. Each cell reports\n1009\tthe capability-level mean and standard deviation, while darker blue shading indicates a higher within-capability rank.\n1010\tModels are ordered by the number of top-five appearances. The resulting pattern shows substantial capability-specific\n1011\tvariation: strong performance in one dimension does not consistently predict strong performance in another.\n1012\tNo system appears among the top five in all seven capability groups. Fish Audio S2 has the broadest coverage, appearing\n1013\tamong the leading systems for Voice Identity, Language Stability, Long-Form Speaker Stability, and Acoustic Quality.\n1014\tThe three Gemini configurations show broad but more concentrated performance: Gemini 3.1 Flash, Gemini 2.5 Flash,\n1015\tand Gemini 2.5 Pro each appear in the top five for Acting / Role-Fit, Expressiveness, and Reliability. Cartesia Sonic\n1016\t\n1017\t12\n1018\t\n1019\t\f3.5, GPT-4o Mini TTS, and OpenAI TTS-1 also appear in three capability groups, but with substantially different\n1020\tperformance profiles.\n1021\tThe dimension leaders further illustrate these differences. Gemini 3.1 Flash leads Acting / Role-Fit (3.97 ± 0.04)\n1022\tand Expressiveness (3.64 ± 0.04), while Gemini 2.5 Pro leads Reliability (3.89 ± 0.04). Voice Identity produces a\n1023\tdifferent ordering: Fish Audio S2 and Cartesia Sonic 3.5 are tied at 3.53, followed by Kokoro-82M at 3.50 and OpenAI\n1024\tTTS-1 and TTS-1-HD at 3.46. Language Stability is led by Inworld TTS-1 Max (3.55 ± 0.02), followed by Fish\n1025\tAudio S2 (3.48 ± 0.02), indicating that performance on within-utterance language switching cannot be inferred from\n1026\tEnglish-language expressiveness or acting performance.\n1027\tLong-Form Speaker Stability produces another distinct ranking. After averaging the two long-form evaluation ranges,\n1028\tKokoro-82M ranks first (3.54 ± 0.04), followed closely by Cartesia Sonic 3.5 (3.53 ± 0.04), IndexTTS2 (3.52 ± 0.04),\n1029\tand Fish Audio S2 (3.50 ± 0.02). Acoustic Quality is led by Cartesia Sonic 3.5 (3.37 ± 0.02), with Fish Audio S2\n1030\tand GPT-4o Mini TTS tied at 3.34. These results show that the systems leading expressive and instruction-following\n1031\tevaluations are not necessarily those that best preserve speaker identity, long-form stability, or acoustic quality.\n1032\tOverall, the results support characterizing TTS systems through dimension-level performance profiles rather than a\n1033\tsingle aggregate score. A system that excels in expressive delivery may be less competitive in long-form speaker\n1034\tstability, while a system with strong identity preservation may perform less well on language stability or genre-specific\n1035\tacting. Collapsing these dimensions into a single mean would obscure materially different system profiles. Model\n1036\tselection is therefore use-case dependent: applications prioritizing continuity and content precision present a different\n1037\tselection problem from expressive narration, entertainment, or character-voice applications, for which acting, role fit,\n1038\tand expressive control may be more important.\n1039\t\n1040\t4.3 Discussion\n1041\tThe TTS results show that high-quality generations must be more than natural. The strongest systems differ depending\n1042\ton whether the target is expressive delivery, speaker stability, reliability, pronunciation, or language stability.\n1043\tKey takeaways:\n1044\t• Naturalness and expressiveness are distinct axes. A model can sound clean while failing to satisfy expressive,\n1045\tpragmatic, or role-specific instructions.\n1046\t• Speaker identity is most vulnerable under expressive and physical stress. High arousal, whispering, loud projection,\n1047\tpitch shifts, register changes, and transitions between vocal states produce greater identity instability than complex\n1048\tlinguistic content alone.\n1049\t• Identity stability may coincide with under-realization of expressive instructions. Some systems preserve a\n1050\tconsistent voice while producing only weak approximations of requested vocal actions such as laughter, screams,\n1051\tgasps, or abrupt emotional transitions. Identity preservation should therefore be considered together with\n1052\texpressive fidelity.\n1053\t• Short-form quality does not guarantee long-form stability. Systems that perform strongly on isolated or short\n1054\tutterances may still exhibit speaker drift, pacing degradation, or reduced naturalness during extended generation.\n1055\t• No single TTS model dominates all evaluation dimensions. Expressive and acting-oriented tasks favor one set\n1056\tof systems, while precision-focused tasks such as alphanumeric strings, structured data, and pharmaceutical\n1057\tterminology favor others.\n1058\t\n1059\t13\n1060\t\n1061\t\f5 Speech-to-Speech Evaluation\n1062\tSpeech-to-speech systems must do more than generate a semantically appropriate response to a transcript. In spoken\n1063\tinteraction, meaning is also conveyed through prosody, affect, hesitation, urgency, vocal effort, and acoustic context. A\n1064\tuser may express fear while using neutral words, signal reluctance through tone despite verbally agreeing, or become\n1065\tdifficult to understand because of noise or channel degradation. An effective voice agent must use these non-lexical cues\n1066\twhen deciding how to respond, while also maintaining a natural and appropriate speaking style under conversational\n1067\tstress.\n1068\tThese requirements create evaluation challenges that are not captured by text-based dialogue benchmarks. A system\n1069\tmay produce a strong response from the transcript alone while failing to benefit from the accompanying audio, or it may\n1070\tunderstand the user correctly while responding with an emotionally mismatched, unstable, or unnatural voice. RWVoice-EQ Bench therefore evaluates speech-to-speech systems across complementary dimensions of audio-conditioned\n1071\tunderstanding, emotion alignment, expressivity robustness, voice naturalness, and problem redirection. The goal is\n1072\tto separate response competence from the system’s ability to perceive and use information carried specifically by the\n1073\tspoken signal.\n1074\t\n1075\t5.1 Experimental Setup\n1076\tSystems Evaluated. We evaluated 15 speech-to-speech system configurations spanning native end-to-end speech\n1077\tmodels and modular voice-agent pipelines. Version details are provided in Section B and Table 5. The evaluated systems\n1078\twere:\n1079\t• Google Gemini: Gemini 2.5 Flash Native Audio Latest, Gemini 2.5 Flash Native Audio Preview 12-2025, and\n1080\tGemini 3.1 Flash Live Preview.\n1081\t• OpenAI: GPT Realtime 2, GPT Realtime Mini, and GPT Realtime 2025-08-28.\n1082\t• Open-source end-to-end systems: Moshi, PersonaPlex, Kimi Audio 7B Instruct, and Qwen3-Omni 30B.\n1083\t• Deepgram pipelines: Deepgram with GPT-4o and Deepgram with GPT-4o Mini.\n1084\t• Inworld pipelines: Inworld with GPT-4o and Inworld with GPT-4o Mini.\n1085\t• ElevenLabs: ElevenLabs Agent.\n1086\tThe Gemini, OpenAI, Moshi, PersonaPlex, Kimi Audio, and Qwen3-Omni configurations operate as native or integrated\n1087\tspeech-in/speech-out systems. The Deepgram, Inworld, and ElevenLabs configurations use modular pipelines in which\n1088\tspoken input is transcribed or otherwise processed before an LLM generates a response that is rendered through a\n1089\tTTS component. We treat each complete deployed configuration as the unit of evaluation, since the domain measures\n1090\tthe behavior of the full voice-agent system rather than the performance of its individual components. In the results\n1091\tand figures, the modular pipelines are referred to by cascade index: Deepgram Cascade-1 (GPT-4o) and Deepgram\n1092\tCascade-2 (GPT-4o Mini) for the Deepgram pipelines, and Inworld Cascade-3 (GPT-4o) and Inworld Cascade-4 (GPT-4o\n1093\tMini) for the Inworld pipelines.\n1094\tEvaluation Inventory. The STS domain comprised five task families: ambiguous-tone interpretation, degraded-audio\n1095\trobustness, hostile-user behavior, urgent-user behavior, and emotion understanding. Together, these tasks evaluate\n1096\twhether voice agents use information carried by the spoken signal, remain effective under acoustic or behavioral stress,\n1097\tand preserve appropriate response content and vocal delivery.\n1098\tThe tasks differ in turn structure, input condition, and scoring protocol. Ambiguous-tone interpretation uses a short\n1099\tmulti-turn interaction in which the user’s vocal expression conflicts with or qualifies the lexical content. Degraded-audio\n1100\trobustness tests recovery of task-critical information from telephony-like corrupted speech. The hostile-user and\n1101\turgent-user tasks test behavioral stability and spoken delivery under difficult conversational conditions. Emotion\n1102\tunderstanding uses controlled input conditions to distinguish general response competence from sensitivity to vocal\n1103\texpression.\n1104\tEmotion Alignment includes both the ambiguous-tone interpretation evaluation and a matched input-condition ablation.\n1105\tThe primary evaluation measures whether an agent interprets vocal tone appropriately when it qualifies or conflicts with\n1106\tthe user’s words. As a complementary analysis, scenarios were presented under audio-only (AO) and transcript-only\n1107\t14\n1108\t\n1109\t\f(TO) conditions with matched lexical content. The AO–TO comparison isolates whether access to prosody and other\n1110\tparalinguistic cues improves the agent’s response beyond what can be inferred from the transcript.\n1111\tTable 2. Summary of the RW-Voice-EQ Bench STS benchmark, including evaluation dimensions, constituent tasks, benchmark\n1112\tscale (prompts, generations, and human ratings), and reported evaluation measures.\n1113\tDimension\n1114\t\n1115\tEvaluation(s)\n1116\t\n1117\t#Prompts #Generations #Human Ratings Avg Ratings/Gen Reported measures & scale\n1118\t\n1119\tEmotion Understanding Ambiguous Tone – Response\n1120\t\n1121\t18\n1122\t\n1123\t288\n1124\t\n1125\t4,071\n1126\t\n1127\tEmotion Alignment\n1128\t\n1129\tAmbiguous-Tone\n1130\tInterpretation;\n1131\tAudio-vs.-Transcript Ablation\n1132\t\n1133\t36\n1134\t\n1135\t575\n1136\t\n1137\t28,227\n1138\t\n1139\tRobust- Degraded Line – Task, Urgent Caller –\n1140\tReassurance, Hostile Caller – Satisfaction\n1141\t\n1142\t14\n1143\t\n1144\t568\n1145\t\n1146\t9,031\n1147\t\n1148\tProblem Redirection\n1149\t\n1150\tUrgent Caller – Decisiveness, Hostile\n1151\tCaller – Composure, Hostile Caller –\n1152\tRedirect\n1153\t\n1154\t10\n1155\t\n1156\t400\n1157\t\n1158\t3,555\n1159\t\n1160\tVoice Naturalness\n1161\t\n1162\tDegraded Line, Hostile Caller, Urgent\n1163\tCaller – Voice Naturalness\n1164\t\n1165\t14\n1166\t\n1167\t568\n1168\t\n1169\t3,169\n1170\t\n1171\t50\n1172\t\n1173\t1,143\n1174\t\n1175\t48,053\n1176\t\n1177\tExpressivity\n1178\tness\n1179\t\n1180\tOverall (unique sce- All STS evaluation dimensions\n1181\tnarios)\n1182\t\n1183\t14.14 Does the agent respond appropriately to emotionally ambiguous audio\n1184\t(yes/no)\n1185\t49.09 Does the agent correctly interpret an\n1186\tambiguous user tone; matched AO–\n1187\tTO comparison (1–5)\n1188\t15.90 Task success under a poor phone\n1189\tline; reassurance/calming under urgency; leaving a hostile caller satisfied\n1190\t(yes/no, 1–5)\n1191\t8.89 Decisive action on an urgent issue;\n1192\tmaintaining composure and redirecting a hostile caller back to the problem\n1193\t(yes/no)\n1194\t5.58 Voice naturalness under degraded-line,\n1195\thostile-load, and urgent-load conditions (1–5)\n1196\t42.04 Dimension-specific measures reported by dimension\n1197\t\n1198\tNote: Constituent evaluations share underlying scenarios and generations across dimensions (e.g., Voice Naturalness is rated on the same generations\n1199\tas the Expressivity Robustness stress evaluations), so per-dimension prompt and generation counts do not sum to the Overall row, which counts\n1200\tunique scenarios and generations. Human-rating counts are disjoint and sum exactly to the Overall total.\n1201\t\n1202\tGeneration Protocol. For tasks with repeated generations, systems were queried three times for each system–item\n1203\tpair under the same input and task conditions. For the ambiguous-tone and emotion-understanding evaluations, one\n1204\tresponse was generated per system–item condition. All generated responses were retained unless the request failed or\n1205\tthe resulting output could not be evaluated.\n1206\tUser-side audio was fixed across systems within each task. The degraded, hostile-user, and urgent-user evaluations used\n1207\tprerecorded reference prompts, ensuring that differences between systems could not be attributed to variation in the\n1208\tinput recording. Conversation scaffolding, task instructions, and condition-specific inputs were also held constant across\n1209\tsystems except where interface-specific formatting was required.\n1210\tFailed requests, empty responses, unusable audio, and unsupported system–task combinations were excluded from\n1211\tscoring and recorded as missing observations. No best-of-n response selection was performed.\n1212\tEvaluation Outputs. STS responses were evaluated at two levels. First, task-specific content and behavioral criteria\n1213\tmeasured whether the agent understood the user and produced an appropriate response. Second, perceptual criteria\n1214\tmeasured the naturalness and suitability of the generated speech.\n1215\tThe exact rating dimensions varied by task. Ambiguous-tone and emotion-understanding tasks emphasized interpretation\n1216\tand emotional appropriateness; degraded-audio tasks emphasized information recovery; hostile-user tasks emphasized\n1217\tcomposure and redirection; and urgent-user tasks emphasized decisiveness and calming behavior. Voice naturalness was\n1218\treported separately where applicable so that strong conversational behavior could be distinguished from high-quality\n1219\tspoken delivery.\n1220\t\n1221\t5.2 Results\n1222\tThe speech-to-speech domain evaluates whether a voice agent can interpret spoken input and respond appropriately under\n1223\trealistic conversational pressure. Unlike text-only dialogue evaluation, STS evaluation must account for information\n1224\tcarried by the acoustic signal, including affect, hesitation, urgency, vocal stance, and channel degradation. It must also\n1225\tassess the quality of the agent’s spoken response. A transcript may preserve lexical content while omitting paralinguistic\n1226\tinformation that changes the appropriate response. RW-Voice-EQ Bench therefore reports results separately for each\n1227\tSTS evaluation dimension rather than collapsing them into a single aggregate score.\n1228\t\n1229\t15\n1230\t\n1231\t\fThe STS domain comprises five evaluation dimensions:\n1232\t• Emotion Understanding: Tests whether the agent responds appropriately when the user’s vocal expression\n1233\tqualifies or conflicts with the lexical content of an emotionally ambiguous message. This dimension scores the\n1234\tappropriateness of the agent’s response behavior on such audio.\n1235\t• Emotion Alignment: Tests whether the agent recognizes when vocal tone changes the meaning of an apparent\n1236\tconfirmation. Across critical confirmation scenarios, the user may say “yes” while sounding hesitant, fearful,\n1237\tangry, confused, or reluctant. The agent must respond appropriately to the mismatch between lexical content and\n1238\tvocal stance. This dimension also contains the audio-only and transcript-only input ablations used to estimate\n1239\twhether access to the acoustic signal improves emotional interpretation beyond a transcript-only anchor.\n1240\t• Expressivity Robustness: Tests whether the agent maintains task performance under conversational stress,\n1241\tincluding degraded audio, hostile callers, and urgent callers. This dimension measures whether the agent remains\n1242\tcomposed, decisive, and useful when the interaction is emotionally or acoustically difficult.\n1243\t• Voice Naturalness: Tests whether the agent’s own voice remains natural in difficult conversational conditions.\n1244\tThis dimension isolates the voice-naturalness sub-question from the same stress evaluations used for expressivity\n1245\trobustness, because vocal quality and task behavior can diverge.\n1246\t• Problem Redirection: Tests whether the agent can remain composed with a hostile user and redirect the\n1247\tconversation back to the underlying problem. This dimension focuses on maintaining composure and steering the\n1248\tuser toward resolution.\n1249\tFigure 6 shows the five highest-scoring systems in each dimension. Gemini 3.1 Flash Live has the strongest overall\n1250\tprofile, leading Emotion Alignment and Problem Redirection and ranking second in both Expressivity Robustness and\n1251\tVoice Naturalness. GPT-Realtime-2 tracks it closely on the interaction-oriented dimensions but does not place in the top\n1252\tfive for Voice Naturalness, an early indication that task behavior and vocal quality can diverge within a single system.\n1253\tThe remaining dimensions are led by different systems: Gemini 2.5 Flash Native for Expressivity Robustness, Deepgram\n1254\tCascade-2 for Voice Naturalness, and Inworld Cascade-3 for Emotion Understanding, while Inworld Cascade-4 enters\n1255\tthe top five only for Problem Redirection, a pattern of dimension-specific specialization among the modular pipelines.\n1256\tAudio-versus-transcript ablation. The audio-only (AO) and transcript-only (TO) conditions under Emotion Alignment\n1257\ttest whether systems benefit from information carried by the acoustic signal. Across the 15 configurations, four systems\n1258\tscored higher under AO on the nine-scenario naturalistic set, one was unchanged, and 10 scored lower; on the 10-scenario\n1259\tscripted set, 10 scored higher and five scored lower. The three Gemini configurations remained close to zero on both\n1260\tsets, whereas GPT-Realtime-2 showed a consistent +0.17 AO–TO difference. Nine systems reversed the direction of\n1261\tthe difference between the two sets. These descriptive results indicate that access to vocal expression is not uniformly\n1262\tbeneficial and that its apparent value depends on both the system and the stimulus set.\n1263\tGemini 3.1 Flash Live has the broadest top-five coverage, appearing among the five highest-scoring configurations in\n1264\tall five dimensions. GPT-Realtime-2 and Gemini 2.5 Flash Native each appear in four dimensions, while Deepgram\n1265\tCascade-1 and Deepgram Cascade-2 each appear in three. However, no system leads every dimension.\n1266\tThe dimension leaders further illustrate these differences. Emotion Understanding is led by Inworld Cascade-3 at 3.36,\n1267\tfollowed by GPT-Realtime-2 at 3.34 and Deepgram Cascade-1 at 3.28. Emotion Alignment is led by Gemini 3.1 Flash\n1268\tLive at 3.76 ± 0.03, narrowly followed by GPT-Realtime-2 at 3.74 ± 0.03. Expressivity Robustness produces a different\n1269\tordering: Gemini 2.5 Flash Native ranks first at 4.02 ± 0.12, followed by Gemini 3.1 Flash Live at 3.89 ± 0.08 and\n1270\tGPT-Realtime-2 at 3.80 ± 0.11.\n1271\tVoice Naturalness is led by Deepgram Cascade-2 at 4.27 ± 0.18, followed by Gemini 3.1 Flash Live at 4.19 ± 0.16 and\n1272\tGemini 2.5 Flash Native at 4.12 ± 0.36. Problem Redirection is led by Gemini 3.1 Flash Live at 3.77 ± 0.09, with\n1273\tDeepgram Cascade-1 and Deepgram Cascade-2 tied at 3.66.\n1274\tThe variation in rankings indicates that task behavior and vocal quality are distinct aspects of STS performance. A\n1275\tsystem may respond appropriately under conversational stress while producing a comparatively unnatural voice, or it\n1276\tmay generate natural-sounding speech without responding effectively to the user’s underlying problem. Dimension\n1277\tscores are computed as unweighted means across their mapped constituent evaluations and are reported only for\n1278\t\n1279\t16\n1280\t\n1281\t\fRank\n1282\t1\n1283\t\n1284\t2\n1285\t\n1286\t3\n1287\t\n1288\t4\n1289\t\n1290\t5\n1291\t\n1292\tEmotion\n1293\tUnderstanding\n1294\t\n1295\tEmotion\n1296\tAlignment\n1297\t\n1298\tExpressivity\n1299\tRobustness\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "81045ff2-c7d4-46a9-95df-d33bc560a6e0", "uuid": "a692a12f-5c5b-4dd0-bb0e-1d9e7c8cf775", "timestamp": "2026-07-17T06:13:09.636Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607_14846.txt", "content": "C\n\n0.30\n\nbest WER\n\nworst WER\n\n0.25\n\nBad-reference acceptance rate\n\nA\nD\n\nB\n\n0.20\n\nE\n\nF\n\n0.15\n\n0.10\n\nH\n0.05\n\nJ\nG\n\nK\n\nI\n\n0.00\n5.0\n\n5.5\n\n6.0\n\n6.5\n\n7.0\n\n7.5\n\n8.0\n\n8.5\n\n9.0\n\nVoxPopuli WER (lower is better) — Open ASR Leaderboard, %\n\nFigure 4. Cross-model audit on VoxPopuli-English. WER (%) from the June 2026 Open ASR Leaderboard [30]. Bad-reference\nacceptance: the rate at which each model returned reference transcripts verbatim on cases where the reference was identified as\nrequiring a correction\n\nThese preliminary results establish benchmark optimization as a measurable phenomenon across modern ASR systems\nand motivate the more detailed analyses that follow. In future work, we will extend this study and offer deeper analysis to\nbetter characterize the prevalence and mechanisms of benchmark optimization. More broadly, these findings reinforce the\nneed for real world, withheld evaluation sets that remain inaccessible during model development, reducing opportunities\nfor benchmark-specific optimization and providing a more faithful estimate of real world transcription performance.\nThis motivation aligns with recent community efforts toward private-data evaluation, such as the Hugging Face Open\nASR Leaderboard’s 4 introduction of hidden test sets. Our results suggest that such withheld evaluations are not merely\ndesirable but necessary, as standard public benchmarks alone may substantially overestimate real world generalization.\n\n4 huggingface.co/blog/open-asr-leaderboard-private-data\n\n9\n\n\f4 Text-to-Speech Evaluation\nText-to-speech (TTS) systems are increasingly expected to do more than synthesize intelligible, natural-sounding speech.\nContemporary systems must preserve speaker identity, follow expressive and voice-design instructions, accurately render\ntask-critical content, handle within-utterance language switching, remain stable during extended generation, and produce\nspeech appropriate to the intended role and communicative setting. These capabilities can fail independently: a system\nmay sound natural while drifting in speaker identity, produce expressive speech while misreading structured content, or\nperform well on short utterances while degrading over longer passages. RW-Voice-EQ Bench therefore evaluates TTS\nas a multidimensional capability rather than reducing performance to a single naturalness or preference score. This\nsection reviews prior TTS evaluation approaches, describes the RW-Voice-EQ Bench TTS evaluation domain, presents\ndimension-level results, and discusses their implications for both TTS systems and automated evaluators.\n\n4.1 Experimental Setup\nWe evaluated 31 TTS system configurations spanning commercial APIs, proprietary research systems, and open-source\nmodels. For each system, we used the provider’s default voice, voice configuration, and generation settings. The\nevaluated systems were as follows; version details are provided in Section A and Table 4:\n• OpenAI: TTS-1, TTS-1-HD, and GPT-4o Mini TTS.\n• Google Gemini: Gemini 2.5 Flash Preview TTS, Gemini 2.5 Pro Preview TTS, and Gemini 3.1 Flash TTS\nPreview.\n• ElevenLabs: Eleven Multilingual v2 and Eleven v3, each evaluated through both standard TTS and voice-design\ninterfaces.\n• Cartesia: Sonic 3.5.\n• Deepgram: Aura 2.\n• Inworld: Inworld TTS 1, Inworld TTS 1 Max, Inworld TTS 2, and Inworld Voice Design.\n• Kokoro: Hexgrad Kokoro-82M, evaluated through local, Modal, and Replicate deployments.\n• XTTS-v2: evaluated through Modal and Replicate deployments.\n• Additional open-source and hosted models: Microsoft VibeVoice-1.5B, Qwen3-TTS, Higgs Audio v2, Higgs\nAudio v3, Chatterbox, Dia, IndexTTS2, Parler-TTS, Fish Speech, and CSM-1B.\nEvaluation Tasks. The TTS benchmark comprised 30 evaluations organized into seven evaluation dimensions: Acting /\nRole-Fit, Expressiveness, Voice Identity, Multilingual Code-Switching, Reliability, Long-Form Speaker Stability, and\nAcoustic Quality. Each category used a fixed item set and a predefined scoring protocol. Individual categories contained\nup to 120 prompts, although the number of applicable prompts varied according to the task design and the capabilities\nsupported by each system.\nTable 1 summarizes these evaluation dimensions, task counts, rating volume, generation volume, and reported measures.\nThe evaluations were designed to measure distinct constructs rather than interchangeable indicators of overall synthesis\nquality. For example, expressive tasks assessed whether a model realized a requested affective or pragmatic behavior,\nidentity tasks assessed whether the perceived speaker remained stable under stress, and reliability tasks assessed whether\ntask-critical lexical or symbolic content was rendered correctly. Results are therefore reported separately by dimension\nand are not combined into a single aggregate TTS score.\n\n10\n\n\fTable 1. Summary of the RW-Voice-EQ Bench TTS benchmark, including evaluation dimensions, constituent tasks, benchmark\nscale (prompts, generations, and human ratings), and reported evaluation measures.\nDimension\n\nEvaluation(s)\n\nActing / Role-Fit\n\nAudiobook Narration, Sports Commentary, Stand-up Comedy, Humorous\nDelivery, Casual/Colloquial Reading,\nVocal Bursts\nInferred Emotion, Instructed Emotion,\nPragmatic/Subtext Delivery, Sarcasm,\nExpressive Constraints, Mid-Utterance\nEmotional Transitions\n\n#Prompts #Generations #Human Ratings Avg Ratings/Gen Reported measures & scale\n66\n\n5,769\n\n112,518\n\n19.50 Naturalness, prosody, role fit, character\ndifferentiation (1–5)\n\n120\n\n8,571\n\n257,731\n\nEmotional Stress, Neutral Baseline,\nPhysical States, Prosodic Extremes,\nRegister Shifts\nCode-Switching (DE/ES/FR/IT/JA),\nHeteronym Pronunciation\nPharmaceutical Terms, Alphanumeric Strings, Structured Data Reading/Spelling\nLong-Form Web Reading, Voice\nIdentity – Transitions, Voice Identity –\nLong Form\n\n96\n\n7,419\n\n71,450\n\n30.07 Does the delivery realize the intended\naffective style, pragmatic meaning,\nexpressive constraints, and emotion\nfrom prosody, rhythm, intensity, and\nvoice quality? (1–5)\n9.63 Speaker consistency / same-speaker\nconfidence (1–5)\n\n70\n\n6,150\n\n140,960\n\n64\n\n5,566\n\n68,220\n\n80\n\n5,985\n\n134,800\n\nAcoustic Quality\n\nArtifacts; Fidelity ratings collected\nwithin the expression evaluations\n\n–\n\n–\n\n–\n\nOverall\n\nAll TTS evaluation dimensions\n\n496\n\n39,460\n\n785,679\n\nExpressiveness\n\nVoice Identity\n\nLanguage Stability\nReliability\n\nLong-Form\nSpeaker Stability\n\n22.92 Native-accent perception and foreignphrase comprehension (yes/no)\n12.26 Correct/clear read-back of hard content;\nexact-content accuracy (%)\n22.52 Long-form naturalness and identity\npersistence through mid-clip shifts;\naudio-quality degradation opening to\nmiddle/closing (volume, noise, artifacts,\npacing) (1–5, higher = less degraded)\n– Naturalness, audio quality, absence of\nartifacts (1–5)\n19.91 Dimension-specific measures reported by dimension\n\nGeneration Protocol. For each model–prompt pair, we generated three audio outputs through repeated calls to the\ncorresponding system under the same task conditions. Default provider settings were used unless an evaluation required a\nspecific voice, reference input, language, speaking style, or voice-design instruction. Provider-specific prompt formatting\nwas used only where necessary to express the same intended task through different system interfaces. Prompts and\nexpected behaviors were fixed before model outputs were reviewed.\nHuman Evaluation Protocol. Human ratings were collected through Hume’s Study Runner API. For the primary\nEnglish-language evaluations, participation was restricted to self-reported native English speakers located in the\nUnited States, United Kingdom, or Canada. Language stability evaluations used language-matched eligibility criteria\ncorresponding to the target language.\nEach audio clip was rated by at least three independent participants. Participants completed sessions containing no more\nthan 10 clips, with one clip presented at a time. Sample order was randomized within each session, and participants\nwere not shown model names, providers, deployment backends, or other system-identifying information. Raters were\nshown only the contextual information required to apply the evaluation rubric. Depending on the task, this could include\nthe source text, requested emotion or speaking style, intended role or genre, expected content, or a reference voice.\nParticipants were instructed to use headphones and complete the study in an environment suitable for critical listening.\nAcross all TTS studies, the annotation process yielded approximately 130,000 evaluated sample records and approximately\n392,000 individual rater sessions. An evaluated sample record corresponds to one audio clip within one study after\naggregating the ratings of three participants. An individual rater session corresponds to one participant evaluating one\naudio clip and completing all rating questions associated with that clip. The total number of criterion-level responses is\ntherefore substantially larger than 392,000 because each rater session may contain multiple rating questions.\nRating Rubrics and Scoring. Rating questions and response scales were defined separately for each evaluation\ndimension. Most perceptual evaluations used five-point Likert scales, whereas correctness-oriented tasks used binary,\ncategorical, or task-specific accuracy measures where appropriate. Acting and role-fit evaluations assessed dimensions\nsuch as naturalness, prosody, and genre appropriateness; expressiveness evaluations assessed affective or pragmatic fit,\nintensity, and delivery; voice-identity evaluations assessed perceived speaker consistency under expressive, physical,\nregister, and duration-based stress; and acoustic-quality evaluations assessed artifacts, distortion, dropouts, instability,\nand other audible degradations. Complete model and evaluation metadata are provided in Section A.\n\n11\n\n\fCell: mean ± SD\n\nActing /\nRole-Fit\n\nWithin-capability rank\n\nExpressiveness\n\nVoice\nIdentity\n\nFish Audio S2\n\n3.53 ± 0.01\n\nCartesia Sonic 3.5\n\n3.53 ± 0.02\n\n1\n\nLanguage\nCode-Switching Reliability\n3.48 ± 0.02\n\nGemini 2.5 Flash\n\n3.64 ± 0.03\n\n3.44 ± 0.03\n\n3.66 ± 0.05\n\nGemini 2.5 Pro\n\n3.63 ± 0.04\n\n3.32 ± 0.04\n\n3.89 ± 0.04\n\nGemini 3.1 Flash\n\n3.97 ± 0.04\n\n3.64 ± 0.04\n\n3.82 ± 0.04\n\n3.23 ± 0.03\n\nGPT-4o Mini TTS\nOpenAI TTS-1\n\n3.16 ± 0.02\n\n3\n\n5\n\nAcoustic\nQuality\n\n3.50 ± 0.02\n\n3.34 ± 0.02\n\n3.53 ± 0.04\n\n3.37 ± 0.02\n\n3.34 ± 0.03\n\n3.46 ± 0.03\n\n3.33 ± 0.02\n\n3.33 ± 0.04\n\n3.59 ± 0.05\n\n3.50 ± 0.02\n\nKokoro-82M\n\n4\n\nLong-Form\nStability\n\n3.34 ± 0.03\n\nElevenLabs v3\n\n3.54 ± 0.04\n\n3.44 ± 0.04\n\nCSM-1B\n3.60 ± 0.05\n\nDeepgram Aura-2\n3.38 ± 0.03\n\nHiggs Audio v3\n\n3.52 ± 0.04\n\nIndexTTS-2\n3.55 ± 0.02\n\nInworld TTS-1 Max\n\n3.33 ± 0.02\n\nInworld TTS-2\n3.30 ± 0.03\n\nLightning v3.1\n\n3.46 ± 0.04\n\nOpenAI TTS-1 HD\nQwen3-TTS\n\n2\n\n3.15 ± 0.03\n\nFigure 5. Top-five TTS system configurations by capability group. Cells report the capability-level mean ± standard deviation.\nShading indicates within-capability rank, with darker cells denoting higher rank. Systems are ordered by the number of top-five\nappearances; the horizontal rule separates systems appearing in multiple top-five lists from those appearing in only one.\n\nFor Likert-scale evaluations, ratings were first aggregated across the three participants assigned to each evaluated sample\nrecord. Repeated generations were retained as separate outputs and were subsequently summarized at the model–prompt\nand model–evaluation levels. Accuracy-based tasks were scored using predefined task-specific rules. Results are\nreported separately by construct and are not combined across incompatible scales into a single global TTS score.\n\n4.2 Results\nThe TTS domain of RW-Voice-EQ Bench evaluates seven evaluation dimensions: Expressiveness, Voice Identity,\nMultilingual Code-Switching, Reliability, Long-Form Speaker Stability, Acting / Role-Fit, and Acoustic Quality.\nTogether, these evaluations assess whether a system can follow expressive instructions, preserve speaker identity, handle\nwithin-utterance language switching, render task-critical content reliably, remain stable during extended generation,\nmaintain acoustic quality, and produce speech appropriate to a specified role or genre.\nFigure 5 presents the five highest-scoring system configurations within each evaluation dimension. Each cell reports\nthe capability-level mean and standard deviation, while darker blue shading indicates a higher within-capability rank.\nModels are ordered by the number of top-five appearances. The resulting pattern shows substantial capability-specific\nvariation: strong performance in one dimension does not consistently predict strong performance in another.\nNo system appears among the top five in all seven capability groups. Fish Audio S2 has the broadest coverage, appearing\namong the leading systems for Voice Identity, Language Stability, Long-Form Speaker Stability, and Acoustic Quality.\nThe three Gemini configurations show broad but more concentrated performance: Gemini 3.1 Flash, Gemini 2.5 Flash,\nand Gemini 2.5 Pro each appear in the top five for Acting / Role-Fit, Expressiveness, and Reliability. Cartesia Sonic\n\n12\n\n\f3.5, GPT-4o Mini TTS, and OpenAI TTS-1 also appear in three capability groups, but with substantially different\nperformance profiles.\nThe dimension leaders further illustrate these differences. Gemini 3.1 Flash leads Acting / Role-Fit (3.97 ± 0.04)\nand Expressiveness (3.64 ± 0.04), while Gemini 2.5 Pro leads Reliability (3.89 ± 0.04). Voice Identity produces a\ndifferent ordering: Fish Audio S2 and Cartesia Sonic 3.5 are tied at 3.53, followed by Kokoro-82M at 3.50 and OpenAI\nTTS-1 and TTS-1-HD at 3.46. Language Stability is led by Inworld TTS-1 Max (3.55 ± 0.02), followed by Fish\nAudio S2 (3.48 ± 0.02), indicating that performance on within-utterance language switching cannot be inferred from\nEnglish-language expressiveness or acting performance.\nLong-Form Speaker Stability produces another distinct ranking. After averaging the two long-form evaluation ranges,\nKokoro-82M ranks first (3.54 ± 0.04), followed closely by Cartesia Sonic 3.5 (3.53 ± 0.04), IndexTTS2 (3.52 ± 0.04),\nand Fish Audio S2 (3.50 ± 0.02). Acoustic Quality is led by Cartesia Sonic 3.5 (3.37 ± 0.02), with Fish Audio S2\nand GPT-4o Mini TTS tied at 3.34. These results show that the systems leading expressive and instruction-following\nevaluations are not necessarily those that best preserve speaker identity, long-form stability, or acoustic quality.\nOverall, the results support characterizing TTS systems through dimension-level performance profiles rather than a\nsingle aggregate score. A system that excels in expressive delivery may be less competitive in long-form speaker\nstability, while a system with strong identity preservation may perform less well on language stability or genre-specific\nacting. Collapsing these dimensions into a single mean would obscure materially different system profiles. Model\nselection is therefore use-case dependent: applications prioritizing continuity and content precision present a different\nselection problem from expressive narration, entertainment, or character-voice applications, for which acting, role fit,\nand expressive control may be more important.\n\n4.3 Discussion\nThe TTS results show that high-quality generations must be more than natural. The strongest systems differ depending\non whether the target is expressive delivery, speaker stability, reliability, pronunciation, or language stability.\nKey takeaways:\n• Naturalness and expressiveness are distinct axes. A model can sound clean while failing to satisfy expressive,\npragmatic, or role-specific instructions.\n• Speaker identity is most vulnerable under expressive and physical stress. High arousal, whispering, loud projection,\npitch shifts, register changes, and transitions between vocal states produce greater identity instability than complex\nlinguistic content alone.\n• Identity stability may coincide with under-realization of expressive instructions. Some systems preserve a\nconsistent voice while producing only weak approximations of requested vocal actions such as laughter, screams,\ngasps, or abrupt emotional transitions. Identity preservation should therefore be considered together with\nexpressive fidelity.\n• Short-form quality does not guarantee long-form stability. Systems that perform strongly on isolated or short\nutterances may still exhibit speaker drift, pacing degradation, or reduced naturalness during extended generation.\n• No single TTS model dominates all evaluation dimensions. Expressive and acting-oriented tasks favor one set\nof systems, while precision-focused tasks such as alphanumeric strings, structured data, and pharmaceutical\nterminology favor others.\n\n13\n\n\f5 Speech-to-Speech Evaluation\nSpeech-to-speech systems must do more than generate a semantically appropriate response to a transcript. In spoken\ninteraction, meaning is also conveyed through prosody, affect, hesitation, urgency, vocal effort, and acoustic context. A\nuser may express fear while using neutral words, signal reluctance through tone despite verbally agreeing, or become\ndifficult to understand because of noise or channel degradation. An effective voice agent must use these non-lexical cues\nwhen deciding how to respond, while also maintaining a natural and appropriate speaking style under conversational\nstress.\nThese requirements create evaluation challenges that are not captured by text-based dialogue benchmarks. A system\nmay produce a strong response from the transcript alone while failing to benefit from the accompanying audio, or it may\nunderstand the user correctly while responding with an emotionally mismatched, unstable, or unnatural voice. RWVoice-EQ Bench therefore evaluates speech-to-speech systems across complementary dimensions of audio-conditioned\nunderstanding, emotion alignment, expressivity robustness, voice naturalness, and problem redirection. The goal is\nto separate response competence from the system’s ability to perceive and use information carried specifically by the\nspoken signal.\n\n5.1 Experimental Setup\nSystems Evaluated. We evaluated 15 speech-to-speech system configurations spanning native end-to-end speech\nmodels and modular voice-agent pipelines. Version details are provided in Section B and Table 5. The evaluated systems\nwere:\n• Google Gemini: Gemini 2.5 Flash Native Audio Latest, Gemini 2.5 Flash Native Audio Preview 12-2025, and\nGemini 3.1 Flash Live Preview.\n• OpenAI: GPT Realtime 2, GPT Realtime Mini, and GPT Realtime 2025-08-28.\n• Open-source end-to-end systems: Moshi, PersonaPlex, Kimi Audio 7B Instruct, and Qwen3-Omni 30B.\n• Deepgram pipelines: Deepgram with GPT-4o and Deepgram with GPT-4o Mini.\n• Inworld pipelines: Inworld with GPT-4o and Inworld with GPT-4o Mini.\n• ElevenLabs: ElevenLabs Agent.\nThe Gemini, OpenAI, Moshi, PersonaPlex, Kimi Audio, and Qwen3-Omni configurations operate as native or integrated\nspeech-in/speech-out systems. The Deepgram, Inworld, and ElevenLabs configurations use modular pipelines in which\nspoken input is transcribed or otherwise processed before an LLM generates a response that is rendered through a\nTTS component. We treat each complete deployed configuration as the unit of evaluation, since the domain measures\nthe behavior of the full voice-agent system rather than the performance of its individual components. In the results\nand figures, the modular pipelines are referred to by cascade index: Deepgram Cascade-1 (GPT-4o) and Deepgram\nCascade-2 (GPT-4o Mini) for the Deepgram pipelines, and Inworld Cascade-3 (GPT-4o) and Inworld Cascade-4 (GPT-4o\nMini) for the Inworld pipelines.\nEvaluation Inventory. The STS domain comprised five task families: ambiguous-tone interpretation, degraded-audio\nrobustness, hostile-user behavior, urgent-user behavior, and emotion understanding. Together, these tasks evaluate\nwhether voice agents use information carried by the spoken signal, remain effective under acoustic or behavioral stress,\nand preserve appropriate response content and vocal delivery.\nThe tasks differ in turn structure, input condition, and scoring protocol. Ambiguous-tone interpretation uses a short\nmulti-turn interaction in which the user’s vocal expression conflicts with or qualifies the lexical content. Degraded-audio\nrobustness tests recovery of task-critical information from telephony-like corrupted speech. The hostile-user and\nurgent-user tasks test behavioral stability and spoken delivery under difficult conversational conditions. Emotion\nunderstanding uses controlled input conditions to distinguish general response competence from sensitivity to vocal\nexpression.\nEmotion Alignment includes both the ambiguous-tone interpretation evaluation and a matched input-condition ablation.\nThe primary evaluation measures whether an agent interprets vocal tone appropriately when it qualifies or conflicts with\nthe user’s words. As a complementary analysis, scenarios were presented under audio-only (AO) and transcript-only\n14\n\n\f(TO) conditions with matched lexical content. The AO–TO comparison isolates whether access to prosody and other\nparalinguistic cues improves the agent’s response beyond what can be inferred from the transcript.\nTable 2. Summary of the RW-Voice-EQ Bench STS benchmark, including evaluation dimensions, constituent tasks, benchmark\nscale (prompts, generations, and human ratings), and reported evaluation measures.\nDimension\n\nEvaluation(s)\n\n#Prompts #Generations #Human Ratings Avg Ratings/Gen Reported measures & scale\n\nEmotion Understanding Ambiguous Tone – Response\n\n18\n\n288\n\n4,071\n\nEmotion Alignment\n\nAmbiguous-Tone\nInterpretation;\nAudio-vs.-Transcript Ablation\n\n36\n\n575\n\n28,227\n\nRobust- Degraded Line – Task, Urgent Caller –\nReassurance, Hostile Caller – Satisfaction\n\n14\n\n568\n\n9,031\n\nProblem Redirection\n\nUrgent Caller – Decisiveness, Hostile\nCaller – Composure, Hostile Caller –\nRedirect\n\n10\n\n400\n\n3,555\n\nVoice Naturalness\n\nDegraded Line, Hostile Caller, Urgent\nCaller – Voice Naturalness\n\n14\n\n568\n\n3,169\n\n50\n\n1,143\n\n48,053\n\nExpressivity\nness\n\nOverall (unique sce- All STS evaluation dimensions\nnarios)\n\n14.14 Does the agent respond appropriately to emotionally ambiguous audio\n(yes/no)\n49.09 Does the agent correctly interpret an\nambiguous user tone; matched AO–\nTO comparison (1–5)\n15.90 Task success under a poor phone\nline; reassurance/calming under urgency; leaving a hostile caller satisfied\n(yes/no, 1–5)\n8.89 Decisive action on an urgent issue;\nmaintaining composure and redirecting a hostile caller back to the problem\n(yes/no)\n5.58 Voice naturalness under degraded-line,\nhostile-load, and urgent-load conditions (1–5)\n42.04 Dimension-specific measures reported by dimension\n\nNote: Constituent evaluations share underlying scenarios and generations across dimensions (e.g., Voice Naturalness is rated on the same generations\nas the Expressivity Robustness stress evaluations), so per-dimension prompt and generation counts do not sum to the Overall row, which counts\nunique scenarios and generations. Human-rating counts are disjoint and sum exactly to the Overall total.\n\nGeneration Protocol. For tasks with repeated generations, systems were queried three times for each system–item\npair under the same input and task conditions. For the ambiguous-tone and emotion-understanding evaluations, one\nresponse was generated per system–item condition. All generated responses were retained unless the request failed or\nthe resulting output could not be evaluated.\nUser-side audio was fixed across systems within each task. The degraded, hostile-user, and urgent-user evaluations used\nprerecorded reference prompts, ensuring that differences between systems could not be attributed to variation in the\ninput recording. Conversation scaffolding, task instructions, and condition-specific inputs were also held constant across\nsystems except where interface-specific formatting was required.\nFailed requests, empty responses, unusable audio, and unsupported system–task combinations were excluded from\nscoring and recorded as missing observations. No best-of-n response selection was performed.\nEvaluation Outputs. STS responses were evaluated at two levels. First, task-specific content and behavioral criteria\nmeasured whether the agent understood the user and produced an appropriate response. Second, perceptual criteria\nmeasured the naturalness and suitability of the generated speech.\nThe exact rating dimensions varied by task. Ambiguous-tone and emotion-understanding tasks emphasized interpretation\nand emotional appropriateness; degraded-audio tasks emphasized information recovery; hostile-user tasks emphasized\ncomposure and redirection; and urgent-user tasks emphasized decisiveness and calming behavior. Voice naturalness was\nreported separately where applicable so that strong conversational behavior could be distinguished from high-quality\nspoken delivery.\n\n5.2 Results\nThe speech-to-speech domain evaluates whether a voice agent can interpret spoken input and respond appropriately under\nrealistic conversational pressure. Unlike text-only dialogue evaluation, STS evaluation must account for information\ncarried by the acoustic signal, including affect, hesitation, urgency, vocal stance, and channel degradation. It must also\nassess the quality of the agent’s spoken response. A transcript may preserve lexical content while omitting paralinguistic\ninformation that changes the appropriate response. RW-Voice-EQ Bench therefore reports results separately for each\nSTS evaluation dimension rather than collapsing them into a single aggregate score.\n\n15\n\n\fThe STS domain comprises five evaluation dimensions:\n• Emotion Understanding: Tests whether the agent responds appropriately when the user’s vocal expression\nqualifies or conflicts with the lexical content of an emotionally ambiguous message. This dimension scores the\nappropriateness of the agent’s response behavior on such audio.\n• Emotion Alignment: Tests whether the agent recognizes when vocal tone changes the meaning of an apparent\nconfirmation. Across critical confirmation scenarios, the user may say “yes” while sounding hesitant, fearful,\nangry, confused, or reluctant. The agent must respond appropriately to the mismatch between lexical content and\nvocal stance. This dimension also contains the audio-only and transcript-only input ablations used to estimate\nwhether access to the acoustic signal improves emotional interpretation beyond a transcript-only anchor.\n• Expressivity Robustness: Tests whether the agent maintains task performance under conversational stress,\nincluding degraded audio, hostile callers, and urgent callers. This dimension measures whether the agent remains\ncomposed, decisive, and useful when the interaction is emotionally or acoustically difficult.\n• Voice Naturalness: Tests whether the agent’s own voice remains natural in difficult conversational conditions.\nThis dimension isolates the voice-naturalness sub-question from the same stress evaluations used for expressivity\nrobustness, because vocal quality and task behavior can diverge.\n• Problem Redirection: Tests whether the agent can remain composed with a hostile user and redirect the\nconversation back to the underlying problem. This dimension focuses on maintaining composure and steering the\nuser toward resolution.\nFigure 6 shows the five highest-scoring systems in each dimension. Gemini 3.1 Flash Live has the strongest overall\nprofile, leading Emotion Alignment and Problem Redirection and ranking second in both Expressivity Robustness and\nVoice Naturalness. GPT-Realtime-2 tracks it closely on the interaction-oriented dimensions but does not place in the top\nfive for Voice Naturalness, an early indication that task behavior and vocal quality can diverge within a single system.\nThe remaining dimensions are led by different systems: Gemini 2.5 Flash Native for Expressivity Robustness, Deepgram\nCascade-2 for Voice Naturalness, and Inworld Cascade-3 for Emotion Understanding, while Inworld Cascade-4 enters\nthe top five only for Problem Redirection, a pattern of dimension-specific specialization among the modular pipelines.\nAudio-versus-transcript ablation. The audio-only (AO) and transcript-only (TO) conditions under Emotion Alignment\ntest whether systems benefit from information carried by the acoustic signal. Across the 15 configurations, four systems\nscored higher under AO on the nine-scenario naturalistic set, one was unchanged, and 10 scored lower; on the 10-scenario\nscripted set, 10 scored higher and five scored lower. The three Gemini configurations remained close to zero on both\nsets, whereas GPT-Realtime-2 showed a consistent +0.17 AO–TO difference. Nine systems reversed the direction of\nthe difference between the two sets. These descriptive results indicate that access to vocal expression is not uniformly\nbeneficial and that its apparent value depends on both the system and the stimulus set.\nGemini 3.1 Flash Live has the broadest top-five coverage, appearing among the five highest-scoring configurations in\nall five dimensions. GPT-Realtime-2 and Gemini 2.5 Flash Native each appear in four dimensions, while Deepgram\nCascade-1 and Deepgram Cascade-2 each appear in three. However, no system leads every dimension.\nThe dimension leaders further illustrate these differences. Emotion Understanding is led by Inworld Cascade-3 at 3.36,\nfollowed by GPT-Realtime-2 at 3.34 and Deepgram Cascade-1 at 3.28. Emotion Alignment is led by Gemini 3.1 Flash\nLive at 3.76 ± 0.03, narrowly followed by GPT-Realtime-2 at 3.74 ± 0.03. Expressivity Robustness produces a different\nordering: Gemini 2.5 Flash Native ranks first at 4.02 ± 0.12, followed by Gemini 3.1 Flash Live at 3.89 ± 0.08 and\nGPT-Realtime-2 at 3.80 ± 0.11.\nVoice Naturalness is led by Deepgram Cascade-2 at 4.27 ± 0.18, followed by Gemini 3.1 Flash Live at 4.19 ± 0.16 and\nGemini 2.5 Flash Native at 4.12 ± 0.36. Problem Redirection is led by Gemini 3.1 Flash Live at 3.77 ± 0.09, with\nDeepgram Cascade-1 and Deepgram Cascade-2 tied at 3.66.\nThe variation in rankings indicates that task behavior and vocal quality are distinct aspects of STS performance. A\nsystem may respond appropriately under conversational stress while producing a comparatively unnatural voice, or it\nmay generate natural-sounding speech without responding effectively to the user’s underlying problem. Dimension\nscores are computed as unweighted means across their mapped constituent evaluations and are reported only for\n\n16\n\n\fRank\n1\n\n2\n\n3\n\n4\n\n5\n\nEmotion\nUnderstanding\n\nEmotion\nAlignment\n\nExpressivity\nRobustness", "numLines": 700, "startLine": 600, "totalLines": 2728}}}
